CONNECTION FLOW OF NETWORK PRINTING
1. User sends print request from application
2. Request goes to Printer Driver & GDI
3. Driver converts data into printer-readable format
4. Job sent to Print Spooler (spoolsv.exe)
5. Spooler stores files in:
C:\Windows\System32\spool\PRINTERS
6. Spool files:
.SPL → Print data
.SHD → Job settings
7. Spooler checks local/network printer
8. For network printer, Point Provider (Win32spl.dll) is used
9. Job sent to remote Print Spooler using RPC over TCP 135
10. Print Server receives/manages job
11. Print Processor & Driver process job
12. Print Monitor sends job to printer
13. Printer prints document
14. Status returned to server/client
15. Spool files deleted automatically

PRINT DRIVERS
Software translating Windows output into printer language
Provided by printer manufacturer
TYPES OF PRINT DRIVERS
TYPE 3 (LEGACY)
Path:C:\Windows\System32\spool\drivers\x64\3
Features:
Vendor provided
Complex management
More storage
More crash prone
TYPE 4 (MODERN)
Path:
C:\Windows\System32\spool\V4Dirs
Features:
Modern class drivers
Windows Update provided
Simplified management
Less storage
More stable

PRINT DRIVER ISOLATION
Isolates print drivers in separate process/container
Used for troubleshooting crashes
PROCESS
PrintIsolationHost.exe
TYPES
NONE-No isolation
SHARED-Drivers isolated in shared container
ISOLATED-Separate container for each driver

